				\begin{document}$${\mathrm{{Ratio}}}_{\mathrm{{{day}}}} = ({\mathrm{{NDVI}}}_{{\mathrm{{day}}}} - {\mathrm{{NDVI}}}_{{\mathrm{{min}}}})/({\mathrm{{NDVI}}}_{{\mathrm{{max}}}} - {\mathrm{{NDVI}}}_{{\mathrm{{min}}}})$$\end{document}Ratioday=(NDVIday-NDVImin)∕(NDVImax-NDVImin), where NDVIday is fitted NDVI at given day, NDVImax and NDVImin are maximum and minimum NDVI each year. A threshold ratio was used to determine SOS and EOS in spring and autumn. Here, we used the threshold 0.237 in method 3 and 0.561 in method 4.

Method 5: A fixed threshold NDVI value was used to determine the phenology. The NDVI season dynamic was calculated from the multiyear NDVI, then the NDVI change rate (NDVIRC) was estimated from the multi-year averaged NDVI seasonal dynamics using the following function: \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
