				\begin{document}$${\mathrm{{NDVI}}}_{\mathrm{{{RC}}}} = \frac{{{\mathrm{{NDVI}}}\left( {t + 1} \right) - {\mathrm{{NDVI}}}(t)}}{{{\mathrm{{NDVI}}}(t)}}$$\end{document}NDVIRC=NDVIt+1-NDVI(t)NDVI(t), where NDVI(t + 1) and NDVI(t) are NDVI value at time t + 1 and t, respectively; The NDVI values correspond to maximum and minimum NDVI change rate are used as the thresholds for SOS and EOS, respectively. The first and second half year NDVI was fitted with a polynomial function: NDVI = a + a1 × t + a2 × t2+···+ an × tn, n = 6, where t is Julian day in a year, and a, a1, a2, …, a6 are fitting parameters. SOS and EOS were determined by comparing the fitted daily NDVI with the thresholds62,63.
